---
import CopyCommand from "../../components/CopyCommand.astro";
import DocsLayout from "../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro";

const installCommand = "curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/nabilrn/MyPaas/main/scripts/bootstrap.sh | bash";
---

<DocsLayout
  title="Installation"
  description="Prepare a Linux VM, launch the bootstrap, and finish setup through the guided installer."
>
  <section>
    <p class="overline">Quick start</p>
    <h2>Start the installer</h2>
    <CopyCommand command={installCommand} label="Ubuntu / Debian" />
    <p>
      The bootstrap installs Git when needed, checks out MyPaas into
      <code>~/MyPaas</code>, and opens the browser setup wizard. It is a starting
      command, not a zero-configuration install.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Prerequisites</h2>
    <table>
      <thead><tr><th>Requirement</th><th>What to prepare</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td><strong>Linux VM or VPS</strong></td><td>Ubuntu or Debian is the supported path for automatic Docker installation.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Cloudflare domain</strong></td><td>An active zone with root and wildcard hostnames routed to the MyPaas Caddy service.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>GitHub OAuth app</strong></td><td>Client ID, client secret, and the correct callback URL for your MyPaas domain.</td></tr>
        <tr><td><strong>Cloudflare Tunnel</strong></td><td>A tunnel token and public hostname routes for the root and wildcard project domains.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
    <aside class="warning"><p>Hardware figures in the PRD describe the original host context. Treat them as planning context, not a universal minimum.</p></aside>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>What the bootstrap does</h2>
    <ol class="steps">
      <li>Checks or installs Git, then creates or safely updates the MyPaas checkout.</li>
      <li>Starts the setup wizard on the VM and attempts a temporary, token-protected Cloudflare Quick Tunnel.</li>
      <li>Falls back to printed SSH port forwarding instructions if the temporary tunnel cannot start.</li>
      <li>Collects the owner email, public domain, GitHub OAuth credentials, Cloudflare Tunnel token, and production secrets.</li>
      <li>Checks Docker and Compose, creates host directories, runs migrations, and starts the production stack.</li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Cloudflare routing</h2>
    <p>Configure both of these public hostname patterns to the MyPaas Caddy service over HTTP:</p>
    <ul>
      <li>The root MyPaas domain, for example <code>mypaas.example.com</code>.</li>
      <li>The wildcard project domain, for example <code>*.mypaas.example.com</code>.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Caddy performs internal routing. Cloudflare Tunnel provides public ingress
      and TLS. Project containers remain bound to local host ports rather than being exposed directly.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2>Verify the installation</h2>
    <pre><code>cd ~/MyPaas
bash scripts/verify-production.sh
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml ps</code></pre>
    <p>
      Confirm the dashboard resolves, the API health check responds, Caddy can be
      reached by the stack, and the Cloudflare root and wildcard records are active.
    </p>
  </section>
</DocsLayout>
